On local to global scales, one of the most rapidly increasing sources of nutrients to both freshwaters and the coastal zone is the atmosphere (Figs. 2 and 3). Phosphate adsorbed onto fine particulates, and nitrate derived from particulate or oxidized nitric/ nitrous oxides in wet and dry deposition, have long been recognized as important sources of nutrients to streams and lakes, and can be major sources especially for softwater, nutrient-poor freshwater systems (Likens et al. 1979; Kilham 1982; Swedish Ministry of Agriculture 1982). In estuarine and coastal waters, it has been estimated that 20-40% of N inputs can be of atmospheric origin, from industrial, agricultural, and urban sources (Duce 1986; Fisher and Oppenheimer 1991; Paerl 1995,

